<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFWeber2006">Weber 2006</a>, p.&#160;387:</span>
<blockquote class="templatequote">
<div class="Bug6200"><span class="reference-text">At the same time, then, as the printing press in the physical, technological sense was invented, 'the press' in the extended sense of the word also entered the historical stage. The phenomenon of publishing was born.</span></div>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Boruchoff 2012, pp. 133-163.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Francis Bacon: "<a href="http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/la:Novum_Organum_-_Liber_Primus" class="extiw" title="s:la:Novum Organum - Liber Primus">Novum Organum, Liber I, CXXIX</a>" − Adapted from the <a href="http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Novum_Organum" class="extiw" title="wikisource:Novum Organum">1863 translation</a>:</span>
<blockquote class="templatequote">
<div class="Bug6200"><span class="reference-text">These three have changed the whole face and state of the world; first in literature, second in warfare, third in navigation; whence have followed innumerable changes, in so much that no empire, no sect, no star seems to have exerted greater power and influence in human affairs than these mechanical discoveries.</span></div>
